1 PhyloSeq setting

#BiocManager::install("phyloseq")

options(conflicts.policy = list(warn = FALSE)) #this line removes all warnings of function masking
library(phyloseq, quietly = TRUE)
library(Biostrings, quietly = TRUE)
library(ggplot2, quietly = TRUE)
library(magrittr, quietly = TRUE)
library(vegan, quietly = TRUE)
theme_set(theme_bw())

#CHANGE PATH according to your settings
setwd("~/Desktop/eDNAworkshop2024")
samdf <- read.delim("PRJNA256993_SraRunTable.txt")
rownames(samdf)<-samdf$Run
samdf<-samdf[,-1]

#convert Collection_Date to a "date"
samdf$Collection_Date<-as.Date(samdf$Collection_Date, "%d.%m.%Y") %>% format("20%y%m%d") %>% as.Date("%Y%m%d")

#read RDS data 
seqtab2.nochim <- readRDS("seqtab2.nochim.rds")
taxa <- readRDS("taxa.rds")

#build phyloseq obj without tree
ps <- phyloseq(otu_table(seqtab2.nochim, taxa_are_rows=FALSE), 
               sample_data(samdf), 
               tax_table(taxa))

#verify the phyloseq object
ps
## phyloseq-class experiment-level object
## otu_table()   OTU Table:         [ 4064 taxa and 24 samples ]
## sample_data() Sample Data:       [ 24 samples by 10 sample variables ]
## tax_table()   Taxonomy Table:    [ 4064 taxa by 7 taxonomic ranks ]

2 rarefaction curves & richness plots

# plotting the rarefaction curve is a quality check to verify that we reached
# saturation of the sampling
rarecurve(data.frame(otu_table(ps, taxa_are_rows = 1)), step = 100, col = "blue",
  lwd = 2, ylab = "ASVs", main = "Rarefaction Curve for all samples")

# When is the saturation reached?

# extract ASV sequences and add them to the phyloseq object renaming the ASVs
dna <- Biostrings::DNAStringSet(taxa_names(ps))
names(dna) <- taxa_names(ps)
ps <- merge_phyloseq(ps, dna)
taxa_names(ps) <- paste0("ASV", seq(ntaxa(ps)))


# Now we check the alpha diversity by plotting different richness indices
# either by Depth or by Fraction vs the position along the river
plot_richness(ps, x = "pos_km", color = "factor(Depth)", measures = c("Shannon",
  "Simpson", "Chao1"))

plot_richness(ps, x = "pos_km", color = "factor(Fraction)", measures = c("Shannon",
  "Simpson", "Chao1"))

# Can you see an effect?

3 Shannon plot with regression

# OK we will focus on the Shannon diversity, but plotting the regression line
# by Fraction size
ps_alpha_div <- estimate_richness(ps, split = TRUE, measure = "Shannon")
sample_metadata <- data.frame(sample_data(ps))
ps_alpha_div$Fraction <- sample_metadata$Fraction[match(rownames(ps_alpha_div), rownames(sample_metadata))]
ps_alpha_div$pos_km <- sample_metadata$pos_km[match(rownames(ps_alpha_div), rownames(sample_metadata))]

ps_alpha_small <- ps_alpha_div[ps_alpha_div$Fraction == "0.2", ]
ps_alpha_large <- ps_alpha_div[ps_alpha_div$Fraction > "0.2", ]
visuals <- rbind(ps_alpha_small, ps_alpha_large)

# plot the regressions with confidence intervals
p3 <- ggplot(visuals, aes(x = pos_km, y = Shannon, group = visuals$Fraction, color = factor(visuals$Fraction))) +
  geom_point() + geom_smooth(data = visuals, method = lm, aes(x = pos_km, y = Shannon,
  group = visuals$Fraction, color = factor(visuals$Fraction)), fill = "#99b3a2",
  se = TRUE, size = 1) + labs(colour = "Fraction")

# Data exploration shows no clear separation

# Now we try to plot the Genus abundance by sample keeping only the first 20
# most abundant taxa.
top20 <- names(sort(taxa_sums(ps), decreasing = TRUE))[1:20]
ps.top20 <- transform_sample_counts(ps, function(OTU) OTU/(sum(OTU) + 1))
ps.top20 <- prune_taxa(top20, ps.top20)
plot_bar(ps.top20, x = "BioSample", fill = "Genus") + geom_bar(aes(color = Genus,
  fill = Genus), stat = "identity", position = "stack")

# Many samples don't contain one of the 20 most abundant taxa! However some
# taxa are typical of fresh water (Acinetobacter, Flavobacter, Rhodoluna,
# Limnohabitans, Pseudarcicella, Sphingorhabdus) or sludge (Luteolibacter)


# plot Phylum abundance of first 1000 most abundant taxa
top1000 <- names(sort(taxa_sums(ps), decreasing = TRUE))[1:1000]
ps.top1000 <- transform_sample_counts(ps, function(OTU) OTU/(sum(OTU) + 1))
ps.top1000 <- prune_taxa(top1000, ps.top1000)
plot_bar(ps.top1000, x = "BioSample", fill = "Phylum") + geom_bar(aes(color = Phylum,
  fill = Phylum), stat = "identity", position = "stack")

6 LEfSe analysis

# Can we identify taxa that are specific for the two fractions? We will use
# LEfSe (Linear discriminant analysis Effect Size) to assess possible
# differences

# BiocManager::install('microbiomeMarker') #if needed
library(microbiomeMarker, quietly = TRUE)
## Registered S3 method overwritten by 'gplots':
##   method         from     
##   reorder.factor DescTools
sample_data(ps)$Fraction <- as.character(sample_data(ps)$Fraction)
lef_out <- microbiomeMarker::run_lefse(ps, group = "Fraction", taxa_rank = "Genus")
microbiomeMarker::plot_ef_bar(lef_out)

# Hey some taxa are known in lake, river or sea (CL500-29 marine group,
# halioglobus, polynucleobacter) or sediment water (gemmatimonas, opitutus,
# brevundimonas, ilumatobacter, sediminibacterium, solitalea) and even some
# potential pathogens (roseomonas)...

# Also typical of human activity, the hgcl-clade group found in areas
# associated with urban and industrial activities.

7 Conclusion

Several tools were introduced to analyse 16S amplicon sequences from different samples along 2600km of the Danube river. The first part related to processing of the read data, QC, cleaning, filtering, error correction, merging, and taxonomy assignment. The second part related to alpha diversity, beta diversity, various plots, geographic localisation, and linear discriminant analysis to highlight some interesting differences and taxas.
